</taxonomicName>
— 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB6CEFAFF95FF834EA0FBB1FDF3FBAB" box="[414,540,1069,1091]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" refId="ref37909" refString="Smith, M. A. (1935) The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma; Reptilia and Amphibia. Fol. II. Sauria. Taylor and Francis, London, 440 pp." type="book">Smith, 1935</bibRefCitation>
. Fauna of British India, ii, 1935: 209.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98B30BFF95FF834FA9FBF3FF0EFB1C" blockId="37.[151,1437,1135,2027]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis id="B9536F19FF95FF834FA9FBF3FE7EFB60" bold="true" box="[151,401,1135,1160]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">Original description.</emphasis>
Gray, J. E. 1831. A synopsis of the species of Class Reptilia. In: Griffith, E &amp; E. Pidgeon: The animal kingdom arranged in conformity with its organisation by the Baron Cuvier with additional descriptions of all the species hither named, and of many before noticed [V Whittaker, Treacher and Co., London: 481 + 110 pp. [1830]
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98B30BFF95FF834FF9FB63FCE9FA6D" blockId="37.[151,1437,1135,2027]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis id="B9536F19FF95FF834FF9FB63FE38FAF0" bold="true" box="[199,471,1279,1304]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">Taxonomic comments.</emphasis>
Gray (1831) failed to mention which specimens he used to describe 
<taxonomicName id="4C27C888FF95FF834A24FA9DFA7AFAF0" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[1306,1429,1280,1304]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Psammophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorsalis">
<emphasis id="B9536F19FF95FF834A24FA9DFA7AFAF0" box="[1306,1429,1280,1304]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">P. dorsalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Currently, there are 
<specimenCount id="9D217882FF95FF834E43FAB8FDF8FAD5" box="[381,535,1316,1341]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" type="generic">20 specimens</specimenCount>
labelled as 
<taxonomicName id="4C27C888FF95FF834D9CFAB9FCF6FAD4" baseAuthorityName="Gray" baseAuthorityYear="1831" box="[674,793,1316,1340]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Psammophilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorsalis">
<emphasis id="B9536F19FF95FF834D9CFAB9FCF6FAD4" box="[674,793,1316,1340]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">P. dorsalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at the Natural History Museum. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB6CEFAFF95FF834BA9FAB8FAB0FAD5" box="[1175,1375,1316,1341]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" refId="ref34283" refString="Boulenger, G. A. (1885) Catalogue of lizards in the British museum. Fol. 1. Geckonidae, Eublepharidae, Uroplatidae, Pygopodidae, Agamidae, Second edition. British Museum (Natural History), London, 436 pp." type="book">Boulenger (1885)</bibRefCitation>
used eight specimens at 
<collectionCode id="ED362BCEFF95FF834E4BFAD4FE59FAB7" box="[373,438,1352,1375]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:14908" name="University of Nottingham" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">NHM</collectionCode>
to describe 
<taxonomicName id="4C27C888FF95FF834D79FAD4FCFCFA88" authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1845" box="[583,787,1352,1376]" class="Reptilia" family="Agamidae" genus="Charasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dorsalis">
<emphasis id="B9536F19FF95FF834D79FAD4FCFCFA88" box="[583,787,1352,1376]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">Charasia dorsalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected from Madras, Nilgiris, Malabar and 
<collectingCountry id="F330F39BFF95FF834A0EFADBFA85FA88" box="[1328,1386,1351,1376]" name="India" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">India</collectingCountry>
and labelled these collections as being from 
<collectingRegion id="49E37DE9FF95FF834D66FAF0FD52FA6D" box="[600,701,1388,1413]" country="Sri Lanka" name="Southern" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">Southern</collectingRegion>
<collectingCountry id="F330F39BFF95FF834DFAFAF0FCEEFA6D" box="[708,769,1388,1413]" name="India" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B98B30BFF95FF834FF9FA13FA79F9B5" blockId="37.[151,1437,1135,2027]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">
There was no precise 
<typeStatus id="549C0DA9FF95FF834EF9FA0CFE18FA40" box="[455,503,1424,1448]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">type</typeStatus>
locality given in the original description but most of the localities mentioned in older publications suggest collections from different parts of southern 
<collectingCountry id="F330F39BFF95FF834CFFFA28FC12FA25" box="[961,1021,1460,1485]" name="India" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">India</collectingCountry>
, especially hilly regions (
<bibRefCitation id="EFB6CEFAFF95FF834A18FA28FF3CFA18" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" refId="ref34329" refString="Boulenger, G. A. (1890) The Fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma: Reptilia and Batrachia. Taylor and Francis, London, 541 pp." type="book">Boulenger 1890</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB6CEFAFF95FF834FDFFA4BFE86FA18" box="[225,361,1495,1520]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438" refId="ref37909" refString="Smith, M. A. (1935) The Fauna of British India, Including Ceylon and Burma; Reptilia and Amphibia. Fol. II. Sauria. Taylor and Francis, London, 440 pp." type="book">Smith 1935</bibRefCitation>
). The chronological collections of the specimens from 
<collectionCode id="ED362BCEFF95FF834CD7FA44FBC5FA07" box="[1001,1066,1496,1519]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:14908" name="University of Nottingham" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">NHM</collectionCode>
need to be verified to choose a 
<typeStatus id="549C0DA9FF95FF834FA9FA60FF11F9FD" box="[151,254,1532,1557]" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">lectotype</typeStatus>
from the specimens at 
<collectionCode id="ED362BCEFF95FF834D31FA61FDBBF9FC" box="[527,596,1533,1556]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:14908" name="University of Nottingham" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">NHM</collectionCode>
. Since there is very little genetic variation (1–2% in 16S mtDNA) in the samples collected from the 
<collectingRegion id="49E37DE9FF95FF834EF3F9BCFDC7F9DF" box="[461,552,1568,1591]" country="Sri Lanka" name="Western" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">Western</collectingRegion>
Ghats of Peninsular 
<collectingCountry id="F330F39BFF95FF834C28F983FCBDF9D0" box="[790,850,1567,1592]" name="India" pageId="37" pageNumber="438">India</collectingCountry>
, we provide an expanded description of this species based on the largest male collected during this study and compare with other specimens collected during the study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
